"Conflict/Contradiction: The conflict arises in the description of what artificial intelligence (AI) refers to. Sources 1, 2, 4, and 7 describe AI as the capability of computer systems to perform tasks associated with human intelligence. Source 3 focuses on AI as a technology that allows for tasks like image analysis and speech recognition. Source 5 mentions AI as a technology that is transforming the modern world and driving innovation. Source 8 expands on AI as technology that enables computers and machines to simulate human learning, comprehension, problem-solving, decision-making, creativity, and autonomy.\n\nReasons for Contradiction: The contradiction may arise due to different perspectives or focuses of the sources. Some sources provide a general definition of AI, while others emphasize specific applications or the transformative impact of AI. The different sources may also be written at different times, reflecting evolving understandings and advancements in AI technology.\n\nConsensus Summary: Artificial intelligence (AI) refers to the capability of computer systems to perform tasks typically associated with human intelligence. It is a technology that enables computers and machines to simulate human learning, comprehension, problem-solving, decision-making, creativity, and autonomy. AI has the potential to transform various industries and drive innovation. Specific applications of AI include image analysis, speech recognition, and complex tasks that involve human reasoning and decision-making."